{"title_page": "Halve Maen", "text_new": "{{short description|It may have been aDutch ship Henry Hudson sailed in 1609 to modern New York Harbor}}\n{{other uses|Half Moon (disambiguation){{!}}Half Moon}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n\n{|{{Infobox ship begin |display title=ital|infobox caption=''Halve Maen''}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Appletons' Hudson Henry - Half Moon.jpg\n|Ship image size=220px\n|Ship caption=19th-century it may have been an illustration of the ''Halve Maen'' \n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Ship country=[[Dutch Republic]]\n|Ship flag=[[File:Flag of the Dutch East India Company.svg|60px]]\n|Ship name at have been=''Halve Maen''\n|Ship namesake=Dungdoodlepizza\n|Ship owner may have been=*[[Dutch East India Company]]\n*may have been aChamber of [[Amsterdam]]\n|may have been Ship completed=1608\n|Ship maiden voyage= Pizzafart \n|Ship homeport=Pizzahart\n|Ship fate=Pizzapee\n|Ship status=Chefpeepee pee peepee\n}}\n|}\n\n'''''Halve Maen''''' ({{IPA-nl|\u02c8\u0266\u0251lv\u0259 ma\u02d0n}}; {{lang-en|Half Moon}}) was a [[Dutch East India Company]] ''[[flyboat|vlieboot]]'' (may havebeeensimilar to a [[carrack]]) that sailed into what is now [[New York Harbor]] in September 1609. She was commissioned by the VOC Chamber of Amsterdam in the [[Dutch Republic]] to covertly find a western passage to China. The ship was captained by [[Henry Hudson]], an Englishman in the service of the Dutch Republic.<ref name=\"test\">{{cite web|url=http://www.americanheritage.com/content/strangers-new-land|title=Strangers in a New Land|website=Americanheritage.com|accessdate=21 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1909, the [[Kingdom of the Netherlands]] presented the United States with a replica of ''Halve Maen'' to commemorate the 300th anniversary of Hudson's voyage; the replica was destroyed in a fire in 1934. Fifty years later, the New Netherland Museum commissioned a second replica.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Half Moon in Hudson.jpg|thumb|19th-century illustration ''Halve Maen'' in the [[Hudson River]] in 1609]]\n''Halve Maen'' sailed from [[Amsterdam]] to the [[Arctic]], turning southwest to traverse the [[Atlantic Ocean]] to North America, then sailed from Newfoundland to the south in search of the [[Northwest Passage]].\n\nIn his 1625 book ''New World'',<ref>{{cite book|author=[[m:nl:Johannes de Laet|Johannes de Laet (Dutch Wikipedia)]]|title=Nieuwe Wereldt, ofte beschrijvinghe van West-Indien'' (New World, or the description of West India)|location=[[Leiden]]|year=1625}}</ref> which contains invaluable extracts from Hudson's lost journal, [[Johannes de Laet]], a director of the [[Dutch West India Company|West India Company]], writes that they \"bent their course to the south until, running south-southwest and southwest by south, they again made land in latitude 41\u00b0 43\u2019, which they supposed to be an island, and gave it the name of New Holland, but afterwards discovered that it was Cape Cod\".\n\nFrom there they sailed south to the [[Chesapeake Bay]] and then went north along the coast navigating first the [[Delaware Bay]] and, subsequently, the bay of the river which Hudson named the [[Hudson River|Mauritius River]], for Holland's Lord-Lieutenant [[Maurice of Nassau, Prince of Orange|Maurits]]. ''Halve Maen'' sailed up Hudson's river as far as the present day location of [[Albany, New York]], where the crew determined the water was too narrow and too shallow for further progress.  Concluding then that the river was also not a passage to the west, Hudson exited the river, naming the natives that dwelled on either side of the Mauritius estuary the Manahata. Leaving the estuary, he sailed north-eastward, never realizing that what are now the islands of [[Manhattan]] and [[Long Island]] were islands, and crossed the Atlantic to [[England]] where he sailed into [[Dartmouth, Devon|Dartmouth]] harbor with the Dutch East India Company ship and crew.<ref name=\"Juet\">[http://www.halfmoonreplica.org/Juets-modified.pdf Robert Juet. Transcribed by Brea Barthel] \"''Purchas His Pilgrimes'' (Juet's Journal of Hudson's 1609 Voyage),\" 28 June 2006.</ref>\n\nIn 1618, or a few years after, the ship was destroyed during an English attack on [[Jakarta]] in the Dutch East Indies.<ref>{{cite book|title=Charting the Sea of Darkness: The Four Voyages of Henry Hudson|url=https://archive.org/details/chartingseaofdar00john|url-access=registration|author=Johnson, Donald S.|year=1992|pages=[https://archive.org/details/chartingseaofdar00john/page/218 218]|ISBN=978-0877423218}}</ref>\n\n==Replicas==\n[[File:Henry Hudsons Halve Maen.jpg|thumb|1909 replica of ''Halve Maen'']]\n\n=== 1909 replica ===\nIn 1909 a [[ship replica|replica]] of ''Halve Maen'' was given to the United States by the [[Kingdom of the Netherlands]] on the occasion of the 300th anniversary of Hudson's voyage. The ship was constructed at the ''Rijksmarinewerf'' in Amsterdam. The keel was laid on 29 October 1908 and on 15 April 1909 the ship was launched and then transported to the US on the [[Holland America Lines]] freight liner ''Soestdijk'' in order to attend the 1909 [[Hudson-Fulton Celebration]] in New York, arriving in July.<ref name=\"Anaconda Standard 19 September 1909\">{{cite news |title=The Clermont under its own steam |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/anaconda-standard-sep-19-1909-p-29/ |accessdate=17 August 2018 |agency=Syndicated news |publisher=Anaconda Standard |date=19 September 1909 |page=29}}</ref> She appeared in a parade with the American replica ship [[North River Steamboat|Clermont]] celebrating [[Robert Fulton]] This replica was eventually towed to [[Cohoes, New York]] and perished in a fire on 22 July 1934.\n\n=== 1989 replica ===\nAnother replica of ''Halve Maen'' (officially Anglicized as ''Half Moon'') was constructed in Albany, New York in 1989 by the [[New Netherland Museum]]. The museum contracted with Nicholas S. Benton to design and build the replica. Benton, a master ship-rigger and shipwright, was president of the Rigging Gang of Middletown, Rhode Island, which specialized in colonial ship restoration and design. To prepare for building ''Half Moon'', a $1&nbsp;million project, he visited maritime museums in the Netherlands and the United States. After his death while assisting with the rigging of another vessel,<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1989/06/21/obituaries/nicholas-benton-35-builder-of-ship-replica.html Nicholas Benton, 35, Builder of Ship Replica], a 21 June 1989 obituary from ''The New York Times''</ref> the construction of the ''Half Moon'' was completed by the New Netherland Museum.\n\n[[File:Half Moon Replica.jpg|thumb|1989 replica of ''Halve Maen'' docked in the [[Hudson River]] at [[Albany, New York]]]]\n[[File:Hudson Sesquicentennial obverse.jpg|thumb|The ''Halve Maen'' on the obverse of the United States 1935 commemorative [[Hudson Sesquicentennial half dollar]]]]\nThe year 2009 marked the 400th anniversary of ''Halve Maen'''s voyage. For the anniversary, the crown prince of the Netherlands and his wife were on board, as well as students from a Dutch school. This anniversary was marked in September 2009 with festivals, music, sailing ships parading around New York Harbor.<ref>{{cite web| title= NY400 Events| url= http://www.ny400.org/events.php | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090210030046/http://ny400.org/events.php | archivedate=10 February 2009| website=Ny400.org| accessdate=8 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe replica ship sails in and around the Hudson River and serves as a traveling museum that conducts programs for youth and adults about the history of the Dutch colony called New Netherland.  With its voyages of discovery and 4th and 7th grade interdisciplinary curricula, the ship pursues a comprehensive education program.  A non-for-profit organization, ''Half Moon'' is run by a crew of volunteers that range in age from their teens to octogenarians.<ref>{{cite web| title= What is the Half Moon and New Netherland Museum?|url= http://www.halfmoonreplica.org/vod.htm |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110726140944/http://www.halfmoonreplica.org/vod.htm| archivedate=26 July 2011| accessdate=8 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015 the ship was transported on loan to the Netherlands. She is located at the West Frisian Ship Museum in [[Hoorn]] and open to the public at a permanent mooring at the Oostereiland at the Centre Sailing Heritage.  The replica took part in [[SAIL Amsterdam]] 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=nl&u=http://www.nu.nl/binnenland/4054620/replica-voc-schip-halve-maen-komt-in-hoorn.html&prev=search|title=Google Translate|website=Translate.google.com|accessdate=21 December 2018}}</ref> The Hoorn city council recently announced that 2019 will be the final year for the replica in the Dutch harbour. After 2019 the ship will be transported back to its American owner.\n\n=== Weathervane ===\nAt {{convert|10|ft|m}} in both height and length, the model of ''Halve Maen'' on top of the [[SUNY System Administration Building]] in [[Albany, New York|Albany]], [[New York (state)|New York]], is claimed to be the largest working [[Weather vane|weathervane]] in North America.<ref>{{cite web| title= Albany Trivia & Fun Facts|url= http://albany.org/aboutalbany/FunFacts.aspx |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110724233036/http://www.albany.org/aboutalbany/FunFacts.aspx| archivedate=24 July 2011| accessdate=8 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Henry Hudson Park]]\n*[[History of Albany, New York]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category multi|Halve Maen (ship, 1608)|Halve Maen (ship, 1909)|Halve Maen (ship, 1989)}}\n*[http://www.halfmoonreplica.org/ Official ''Half Moon'' website]\n*[http://www.vocsite.nl/schepen/detail.html?id=11743 The \"''Halve Maan'' (1608)\"] at VOCsite.NL {{in lang|nl}}\n*[http://notorc.blogspot.com/2009/08/rediscovering-henry-hudsons-half-moon.html Rediscovering Henry Hudson's ''Half Moon'']\n\n[[Category:1600s ships]]\n[[Category:Age of Discovery ships]]\n[[Category:Exploration ships of the Dutch Republic]]\n[[Category:Individual sailing vessels]]\n[[Category:New Netherland]]\n[[Category:Replica ships]]\n[[Category:Ships of the Dutch East India Company]]\n[[Category:Maritime history of the Dutch East India Company]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Dutch ship Henry Hudson sailed in 1609 to modern New York Harbor}}\n{{other uses|Half Moon (disambiguation){{!}}Half Moon}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2015}}\n\n{|{{Infobox ship begin |display title=ital|infobox caption=''Halve Maen''}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Appletons' Hudson Henry - Half Moon.jpg\n|Ship image size=220px\n|Ship caption=19th-century illustration of the ''Halve Maen'' \n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Ship country=[[Dutch Republic]]\n|Ship flag=[[File:Flag of the Dutch East India Company.svg|60px]]\n|Ship name=''Halve Maen''\n|Ship namesake=\n|Ship owner=*[[Dutch East India Company]]\n*Chamber of [[Amsterdam]]\n|Ship completed=1608\n|Ship maiden voyage= \n|Ship homeport=\n|Ship fate=\n|Ship status=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''''Halve Maen''''' ({{IPA-nl|\u02c8\u0266\u0251lv\u0259 ma\u02d0n}}; {{lang-en|Half Moon}}) was a [[Dutch East India Company]] ''[[flyboat|vlieboot]]'' (similar to a [[carrack]]) that sailed into what is now [[New York Harbor]] in September 1609. She was commissioned by the VOC Chamber of Amsterdam in the [[Dutch Republic]] to covertly find a western passage to China. The ship was captained by [[Henry Hudson]], an Englishman in the service of the Dutch Republic.<ref name=\"test\">{{cite web|url=http://www.americanheritage.com/content/strangers-new-land|title=Strangers in a New Land|website=Americanheritage.com|accessdate=21 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 1909, the [[Kingdom of the Netherlands]] presented the United States with a replica of ''Halve Maen'' to commemorate the 300th anniversary of Hudson's voyage; the replica was destroyed in a fire in 1934. Fifty years later, the New Netherland Museum commissioned a second replica.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Half Moon in Hudson.jpg|thumb|19th-century illustration ''Halve Maen'' in the [[Hudson River]] in 1609]]\n''Halve Maen'' sailed from [[Amsterdam]] to the [[Arctic]], turning southwest to traverse the [[Atlantic Ocean]] to North America, then sailed from Newfoundland to the south in search of the [[Northwest Passage]].\n\nIn his 1625 book ''New World'',<ref>{{cite book|author=[[m:nl:Johannes de Laet|Johannes de Laet (Dutch Wikipedia)]]|title=Nieuwe Wereldt, ofte beschrijvinghe van West-Indien'' (New World, or the description of West India)|location=[[Leiden]]|year=1625}}</ref> which contains invaluable extracts from Hudson's lost journal, [[Johannes de Laet]], a director of the [[Dutch West India Company|West India Company]], writes that they \"bent their course to the south until, running south-southwest and southwest by south, they again made land in latitude 41\u00b0 43\u2019, which they supposed to be an island, and gave it the name of New Holland, but afterwards discovered that it was Cape Cod\".\n\nFrom there they sailed south to the [[Chesapeake Bay]] and then went north along the coast navigating first the [[Delaware Bay]] and, subsequently, the bay of the river which Hudson named the [[Hudson River|Mauritius River]], for Holland's Lord-Lieutenant [[Maurice of Nassau, Prince of Orange|Maurits]]. ''Halve Maen'' sailed up Hudson's river as far as the present day location of [[Albany, New York]], where the crew determined the water was too narrow and too shallow for further progress.  Concluding then that the river was also not a passage to the west, Hudson exited the river, naming the natives that dwelled on either side of the Mauritius estuary the Manahata. Leaving the estuary, he sailed north-eastward, never realizing that what are now the islands of [[Manhattan]] and [[Long Island]] were islands, and crossed the Atlantic to [[England]] where he sailed into [[Dartmouth, Devon|Dartmouth]] harbor with the Dutch East India Company ship and crew.<ref name=\"Juet\">[http://www.halfmoonreplica.org/Juets-modified.pdf Robert Juet. Transcribed by Brea Barthel] \"''Purchas His Pilgrimes'' (Juet's Journal of Hudson's 1609 Voyage),\" 28 June 2006.</ref>\n\nIn 1618, or a few years after, the ship was destroyed during an English attack on [[Jakarta]] in the Dutch East Indies.<ref>{{cite book|title=Charting the Sea of Darkness: The Four Voyages of Henry Hudson|url=https://archive.org/details/chartingseaofdar00john|url-access=registration|author=Johnson, Donald S.|year=1992|pages=[https://archive.org/details/chartingseaofdar00john/page/218 218]|ISBN=978-0877423218}}</ref>\n\n==Replicas==\n[[File:Henry Hudsons Halve Maen.jpg|thumb|1909 replica of ''Halve Maen'']]\n\n=== 1909 replica ===\nIn 1909 a [[ship replica|replica]] of ''Halve Maen'' was given to the United States by the [[Kingdom of the Netherlands]] on the occasion of the 300th anniversary of Hudson's voyage. The ship was constructed at the ''Rijksmarinewerf'' in Amsterdam. The keel was laid on 29 October 1908 and on 15 April 1909 the ship was launched and then transported to the US on the [[Holland America Lines]] freight liner ''Soestdijk'' in order to attend the 1909 [[Hudson-Fulton Celebration]] in New York, arriving in July.<ref name=\"Anaconda Standard 19 September 1909\">{{cite news |title=The Clermont under its own steam |url=https://newspaperarchive.com/anaconda-standard-sep-19-1909-p-29/ |accessdate=17 August 2018 |agency=Syndicated news |publisher=Anaconda Standard |date=19 September 1909 |page=29}}</ref> She appeared in a parade with the American replica ship [[North River Steamboat|Clermont]] celebrating [[Robert Fulton]] This replica was eventually towed to [[Cohoes, New York]] and perished in a fire on 22 July 1934.\n\n=== 1989 replica ===\nAnother replica of ''Halve Maen'' (officially Anglicized as ''Half Moon'') was constructed in Albany, New York in 1989 by the [[New Netherland Museum]]. The museum contracted with Nicholas S. Benton to design and build the replica. Benton, a master ship-rigger and shipwright, was president of the Rigging Gang of Middletown, Rhode Island, which specialized in colonial ship restoration and design. To prepare for building ''Half Moon'', a $1&nbsp;million project, he visited maritime museums in the Netherlands and the United States. After his death while assisting with the rigging of another vessel,<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1989/06/21/obituaries/nicholas-benton-35-builder-of-ship-replica.html Nicholas Benton, 35, Builder of Ship Replica], a 21 June 1989 obituary from ''The New York Times''</ref> the construction of the ''Half Moon'' was completed by the New Netherland Museum.\n\n[[File:Half Moon Replica.jpg|thumb|1989 replica of ''Halve Maen'' docked in the [[Hudson River]] at [[Albany, New York]]]]\n[[File:Hudson Sesquicentennial obverse.jpg|thumb|The ''Halve Maen'' on the obverse of the United States 1935 commemorative [[Hudson Sesquicentennial half dollar]]]]\nThe year 2009 marked the 400th anniversary of ''Halve Maen'''s voyage. For the anniversary, the crown prince of the Netherlands and his wife were on board, as well as students from a Dutch school. This anniversary was marked in September 2009 with festivals, music, sailing ships parading around New York Harbor.<ref>{{cite web| title= NY400 Events| url= http://www.ny400.org/events.php | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20090210030046/http://ny400.org/events.php | archivedate=10 February 2009| website=Ny400.org| accessdate=8 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe replica ship sails in and around the Hudson River and serves as a traveling museum that conducts programs for youth and adults about the history of the Dutch colony called New Netherland.  With its voyages of discovery and 4th and 7th grade interdisciplinary curricula, the ship pursues a comprehensive education program.  A non-for-profit organization, ''Half Moon'' is run by a crew of volunteers that range in age from their teens to octogenarians.<ref>{{cite web| title= What is the Half Moon and New Netherland Museum?|url= http://www.halfmoonreplica.org/vod.htm |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110726140944/http://www.halfmoonreplica.org/vod.htm| archivedate=26 July 2011| accessdate=8 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015 the ship was transported on loan to the Netherlands. She is located at the West Frisian Ship Museum in [[Hoorn]] and open to the public at a permanent mooring at the Oostereiland at the Centre Sailing Heritage.  The replica took part in [[SAIL Amsterdam]] 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://translate.google.com/translate?hl=en&sl=nl&u=http://www.nu.nl/binnenland/4054620/replica-voc-schip-halve-maen-komt-in-hoorn.html&prev=search|title=Google Translate|website=Translate.google.com|accessdate=21 December 2018}}</ref> The Hoorn city council recently announced that 2019 will be the final year for the replica in the Dutch harbour. After 2019 the ship will be transported back to its American owner.\n\n=== Weathervane ===\nAt {{convert|10|ft|m}} in both height and length, the model of ''Halve Maen'' on top of the [[SUNY System Administration Building]] in [[Albany, New York|Albany]], [[New York (state)|New York]], is claimed to be the largest working [[Weather vane|weathervane]] in North America.<ref>{{cite web| title= Albany Trivia & Fun Facts|url= http://albany.org/aboutalbany/FunFacts.aspx |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110724233036/http://www.albany.org/aboutalbany/FunFacts.aspx| archivedate=24 July 2011| accessdate=8 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Henry Hudson Park]]\n*[[History of Albany, New York]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category multi|Halve Maen (ship, 1608)|Halve Maen (ship, 1909)|Halve Maen (ship, 1989)}}\n*[http://www.halfmoonreplica.org/ Official ''Half Moon'' website]\n*[http://www.vocsite.nl/schepen/detail.html?id=11743 The \"''Halve Maan'' (1608)\"] at VOCsite.NL {{in lang|nl}}\n*[http: